<h4>How do you get your ideas?</h4>
<p>I could fill an entire website answering this question.  Ideas come out of my life, a favorite setting prompted <span class="italic">Maggie&rsquo;s Whopper</span>, for instance.  An exciting experience triggered <span class="italic">Sarah&rsquo;s Surprise</span>, a hike along the rocky coast of Maine in search of shellfish and mussels.  Most writers advise others to write what they know, what they are expert in.  I&rsquo;m an expert in blindness, and many of my books deal with that. </p>

<h4>Will you visit my school?</h4>
<p>Gladly.  Here is my contact information: <a href="mailto:shalexan@verizon.net">shalexan@verizon.net</a></p>

<h4>How do you think of titles?</h4>
<p>Ah, titles are difficult for me.  Of the eight books I&rsquo;ve published, I&rsquo;ve only sold two whose titles stuck: <span class="italic">Maggie&rsquo;s Whopper</span> and <span class="italic">On My Own: the Journey Continues</span>.  My title for <span class="italic">Mom Can&rsquo;t See Me</span> was &ldquo;My Mom is Blind&rdquo;, boring, right?  My name for <span class="italic">Sarah&rsquo;s Surprise</span> was &ldquo;Rescue at Baldhead,&rdquo; a dead give-away of the plot.  I had fun with my editor, sending a list of joke titles before a friend suggested <span class="italic">Mom&rsquo;s Best Friend</span>, a play on &ldquo;man&rsquo;s best friend.&rdquo;  A few of my humorous entries were &ldquo;The Tail that Wags Mom,&rdquo; &ldquo;Mom will Never Walk Alone,&rdquo; and &ldquo;The Quick and the Dead.&rdquo;  After all my jokes, my editor never knew if I was serious when I entitled a new manuscript.</p>

<h4>What is your favorite book?</h4>
<p>Just as I cannot tell you which of our two kids is my favorite, I cannot choose a favorite book I&rsquo;ve written.  
I&rsquo;m happy with each of them, thankfully.  I&rsquo;d hate to cringe when hearing certain passages from a published book, because 
I can&rsquo;t do a thing to fix it.  As far as favorite books of all time, written by others, I love <span class="italic">Middlemarch</span> by Eliot and 
<span class="italic">Pride and Prejudice</span> by Austen.  Since I read constantly, I&rsquo;m always finding astonishing other books, such as 
<span class="italic">The Life of Pi</span> by Martel and <span class="italic">Howard&rsquo;s End</span> by Forster.  Every week I have a new favorite.  
Favorite children&rsquo;s books would fill a website, but here are a few: <span class="italic">Danny, the Champion of the World</span>; <span class="italic">Boy</span>; 
and <span class="italic">Going Solo</span>, all by Dahl; <span class="italic">Number the Stars</span>, Lowry; <span class="italic">Harris and Me</span>, Paulsen; 
<span class="italic">So Far from the Bamboo Grove</span>, Watkins; <span class="italic">Carver: A Life in Poems</span>, Nelson; 
<span class="italic">Ella Enchanted</span>, Levine; any book by Mildred Taylor; <span class="italic">Freak, the Mighty</span>, Philbrick; 
<span class="italic">The Fault in Our Stars</span>, Green; <span class="italic">The Absolutely True Diary of a Part Time Indian</span>, Alexi; and I'm really 
a push-over for dystopian Y.A. books, the <span class="italic">Matched</span> series by Condie or the <span class="italic">Delirium</span> series by Oliver; 
Then there are the classics in children's literature, <span class="italic">Charlotte's Web</span>, <span class="italic">The Secret Garden</span>, and 
<span class="italic">Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm</span>.</p>

<h4>How long does it take to write a book?</h4>
<p>It varies.  I wrote <span class="italic">Taking Hold: My Journey into Blindness</span> first as fiction.  I didn&rsquo;t want to write an autobiography, because an author exposes much more of herself than she wants.  Autobiographies also embarrass the author&rsquo;s friends and loved ones. I wrote and re-wrote that fictional version for about a year; my editor rejected it, saying she wanted my story.  I resisted, but finally gave in and wrote my story.  That took almost another year. The shortest time I spent on a book was six months.  The longest time was probably four years, <span class="italic">Mom Can&rsquo;t See Me</span>.  I wrote it first as a photo-essay, taking Joel to school.  Friends in my writing group liked the content, but thought the pictures would be boring, all houses and sidewalks, and then, whoopee!  A school.  So I re-wrote it as a picture book about a seven-year old boy bringing a new friend home from school.  I called it, &ldquo;What Will He Think of Mom?&rdquo;  An editor sent me a two-page, single-spaced letter, asking for a re-write.  She wanted it to be a novel.  I wrote a one-hundred page novel.  Finally, I turned it back to a photo-essay, this time using my daughter, Leslie&rsquo;s, point of view.  I wrote that version in six weeks and sold it immediately.  Actually, now that I think about it, the book that took the longest to write was <span class="italic">She touched the World: Laura Bridgman: Deaf-Blind Pioneer</span>, over six years.  Research for a biography is very time-consuming, and I wrote it first as a one-hundred-and-fifty page book, then a mid grade, and then a picture book, finally choking the life out of it.  I absolutely thought I would be writing that book in the nursing home.</p>

<h4>How can I get to be a writer?</h4>
<p>There is no guaranteed route.  But I&rsquo;d suggest reading endlessly.  Read happily, then read critically.  Read books for kids; read books for adults, even books for dogs, if such exist.  Then, go out and live your life.  Living doesn&rsquo;t mean sitting in front of TV.  Be a doer.  Books come out of living, out of interacting with people and the world.</p>

<h4>Is it hard to be blind?</h4>
<p>Frankly, yes—sometimes.  Sight is very convenient.  Most people walk around without much thought of how it&rsquo;s done.  They can walk, chew gum, talk on a cell phone, listen to a radio, talk, daydream, etc.  Blind people can&rsquo;t walk without using one hundred per cent of their brains to do it.  Sight is also a pleasure.  It&rsquo;s a lovely thing to see the ocean or a snow-capped mountain.  Blindness is a loss—no doubt about it.  It takes me more time to do things than when I could see.  But the challenge of blindness, like most challenges, gives the opportunity to grow and learn and change.  Blindness has improved me in many ways.  One student asked me, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t pity you; should I?&rdquo;  Absolutely not.  My life is very happy; I feel extremely lucky.</p>

<h4>Questions about blindness:</h4>
<p>Please check out my book, <span class="italic">Do You Remember the Color Blue?</span>  In that book, I&rsquo;ve answered the most frequently-asked questions about blindness.  I explain how I do daily tasks, such as cooking, how the dog works, how I became blind, what it was like to be a blind parent, how I read, write, whether people treat me differently, whether being blind has changed me, and various other questions, such as why blind people wear sunglasses.</p>
